Part 2

Dr. Sen was sitting at the corner wooden table of the hospital visitor's room. She was fifty, perhaps fifty-two years old, wearing a simple silk saree that had the dull grey color of river silt. 

She had three folders placed neatly on the table, their brown cardboard covers held together by thin, red cotton strings.

"I expected you earlier, Dr. Tripathy," she said, looking up as he walked in.

Adarsh sat in the wooden chair across from her, resting his hands on the table. "The morning shift took some time to transition," he said.

"Sarita brought him to my clinic in Shobhabazar in 2016," she said, opening the first folder. "He had been found sitting in the Alipore garage, staring at the empty silver sedan for eight hours without moving."

Adarsh looked at the papers inside the folder. The notes were written in a quick, clinical hand, with dates and observations covering the margins.

"He told me about Rehman," she said. "He described the canvas bag, the rusted zip, the way the boy painted the kitchen, even his Odia accent. He said the boy had Ira's eyes."

"Ira," Adarsh said, his voice quiet.

"He carried her memory like a stone in his shoe," she said. "Every step hurt, but he had stopped trying to shake it out."

She turned a page, the paper making a dry, sharp rustle in the quiet room. 

"The yellow envelope was real," she said. "But it was only a municipal tax receipt. Vikram needed a reason to let the boy in. So his split mind read Ira's name on the cheap yellow paper."

"Why did he need the projection?" Adarsh asked.

"Because he was tired of the split," she said, looking out through the window at the hospital parking lot. "One half of him had built the fourteen hundred crore. The other half had left the anatomy lab in ninety-six, leaving a textbook half-underlined. He wanted the well, but the tycoon in him couldn't stop building."

She tapped the brown folder with her finger. 

"Rehman was the alternate choice. The boy who could buy the silver sedan, fly to Geneva, and run the business, while Vikram slept on the wooden bench in Bagbazar. Rehman was the one who could shout at him on the terrace."

"The terrace," Adarsh said. "The candle and the sun."

"It was Vikram's own voice," she said, looking at him. "He had given the entire empire to Rohan. He had walked away. But even in Bagbazar, the local MLA still called him *Ahuja saab*. He couldn't escape the name. He was guilty that his legacy followed him."

She closed the folder. 

"The real Ira Sen appearing at the press meet broke the split. The moment she said she never had a son, the alternate choice had to end. Rehman had to disappear."

"Did Vikram know?" Adarsh asked.

"He knew," she said. "He told me he signed the CEO transfer with a blue blur because the space for the second name was blank. He said: *I wanted to give the pen to Rehman. But Rehman had no hand to take it.*"

She stood up. She tied the red string around the cardboard folder, the knot tight, neat, and final.

"His case was simple, Dr. Tripathy. Some minds break because they are weak. His broke because it was too honest to keep the palace and the well at the same time."

She looked at him before picking up the files. "His smiles were transparent," she said. "But his tears... they had no color."

Adarsh sat in the wooden chair, silent. The visitor's room was completely quiet now. 

The lawyer's deeds were in Dalhousie Square, the Alipore house was locked, and the factory compound gates in Nandyal were opening and closing. But the case file on the table was the only thing that had his friend's name written on the cover.

"Thank you, doctor," Adarsh said.

She picked up the folders and left. Her leather sandals made a quiet, clicking sound against the corridor floor, fading away until only the scratching sound of the old ceiling fan remained in the room.

[End of Part 2]
